{{!-- DIV #2 RULES --}}
<div class="container">
    <div class="card-panel">
        <div class="row">
            <form class="col s12">
                <div class="row">
                    <div class="col s12 m6 center-align">
                        <img id="infographic-profile" src="assets/images/tbInfographic.png">
                    </div>
                    <div class="col s12 m6">
                        <h2>How to Play</h2>
                        <p>In order to play the game, you first need a deck of 20 cards. If you don't have
                            one, head to the deckbuilder to create one. Once your deck is done, click on
                            the arena to battle.</p><p> You and your opponent will each start with a hand 
                            of 3 cards from your deck. Click on one of your cards to play it, your opponent
                            will do the same. Use the rules picture to determine which card will be
                            victorious. The winner's card will go to their discard pile, the loser's will
                            be destroyed. In the case of a draw, both cards are destroyed. </p><p> Click 
                            the "Next Round" button and both players will draw another card from their 
                            deck. If your deck is empty, your discard pile will be shuffled back in. The 
                            game continues until a player is out of cards, rendering them the loser.</p> 
                            <p>Happy Playing!</p><br><p>(How to read the rules infographic):</p><p>First,
                            count the number of steps between the two cards being evaluated. For example,
                            if a red card is against an orange card, there are 3 steps between those colors
                            on the diagram. Next, read the rule that corresponds to that number of steps. In
                            our example, 3 steps means the higher numbered card wins. If the colors are the
                            same, the number closer to 7 wins. If the colors are next to each other, the 
                            color that is more counter-clockwise wins (i.e. red beats gray, gray beats blue,
                            etc...), 2 steps means the low card wins, 3 steps is high card, and 4 steps means
                            the number furthest from 7 wins.</p>
                    </div>
                </div>
            </form>
        </div>
    </div>
</div>